Use `elan` to install each candidate nightly between the last-known-good and first-known-bad toolchains, then run `lake env lean Test.lean` (or `lean --run Test.lean`) on the self-contained file inside a git-managed scratch repo with `lean-toolchain` pinned per iteration. Drive the search with `git bisect run` over a tags branch of `leanprover/lean4` nightlies, where the run-script sets `lean-toolchain`, invokes `elan toolchain install $(cat lean-toolchain)`, then `lake env lean Test.lean`, exiting 0 on success and 1 on the regression signature (nonzero status, specific error message, or timeout). Log stderr per nightly to disambiguate genuine regressions from infrastructure flakes, and re-run any "skip" (exit 125) toolchain that fails to download. Bisect converges in ⌈log2 N⌉ steps over N nightlies; for a typical month-wide window that is 5–6 builds. Confirm the culprit by diffing `lean4` between the good and bad nightly tags (`git log good..bad`) and minimising the test to the smallest failing declaration. Report the offending nightly tag, the suspect commit range, and a minimised MWE upstream at `leanprover/lean4/issues`.
